title: XC447012 Barred Owl (Strix varia)
type: alarm call, call, caterwaul, duet, female, male, song
description:
This is a re-submission of our original audio recording.  A noise reduction followed by a minor (4 dB) sound amplification was superimposed to the audio recording.

We were on our honeymoon in north Georgia. We sat on the back porch of our cabin, overlooking the Blue Ridge Mountains and began calling into the woods just after sunset. Not long after, we received our first barred owl response! Then several different groups of barred owls all began responding to us from the trees at many different points around the cabin! Never did we expect to hear so many all at once. We were thrilled and carried on a back-and-forth conversation with these noisy nocturnal predators for nearly an hour, full of hoots, wails and caterwauls. We took a one minute trim of the recording for submission her.
author: Michael & Katie LaTour

This recording was made from two different segments captured during the second visit. Most of the birds were hiding in reeds, weeds, and/or bushes. The few glimpses we caught were not really identifiable as Swamp Sparrow, and I thought they were not red enough (fall plumage) but the call seems to match.

secondary_labels: ['Empidonax alnorum_Alder Flycatcher', 'Mniotilta varia_Black-and-white Warbler', 'Setophaga ruticilla_American Redstart']
description: Recording amplified by 5.  Originally I'd paused to record the Alder Flycatcher, since it was close.  As I turned the recorder on, I heard the 'perwee' sound that I've attributed to the Yellow-bellied Flycatcher.  The sound doesn't fit exactly, but seems to be the best match.  The bird in question calls at 0:00.3, 0:04.0, 0:08.0, 0:15.9, and at 0:27.6 seconds.  Bird was not seen.  Note a Least Flycatcher was singing for a few min before and after this recording.  This recording was from the dense understory adjacent to a swampy wooded wetland.  There were alder trees present.  All birds were well back and tucked in the understory.
background: Alder Flycatcher (Empidonax alnorum); Black-and-white Warbler (Mniotilta varia); American Yellow Warbler (Setophaga aestiva); American Redstart (Setophaga ruticilla)

title: XC165398 Canada Goose (Branta canadensis)
description:
A large flock of Canada Geese taking off. I believe most of the birds in this flock were parvipes ("Lesser") Canada Geese, but there were also larger (subspecies moffitti?) Canada Geese and a few Cackling Geese (several of the subspecies hutchinsii and possibly one of the subspecies minima) in the general vicinity. 

In the old days this would have been an "obvious" or "easy" flock of "Canada Geese." Now we're dealing with perhaps two species and probably two or three subspecies in the recording. Again, I believe most of the birds audible here are parvipes ("Lesser") Canada Geese.

title: XC297982 Barred Owl (Strix varia)
location: Blake Road, Sidney, Kennebec County, Maine
description:
Previously entered as "unknown" but now identified as a barred owl.  I am leaving the orginal comments below for the sake of completeness. Thank you to everyone for your comments!  --Lance



Unknown sound.  Heard after playing a great horned owl recording.   The sounds continued after I played barred owl, northern saw-whet owl, and long-eared owl recordings.  The source of the sounds moved at least twice during the ~25 minutes that I heard it.

I have heard barred and northern saw-whet owl at this location previously (most recently only about six weeks earlier) but this sound doesn't match any by those species that I've ever heard.  I checked every barred owl recording on Xeno-Canto and in the Cornell Master Set but these vocalizations don't match any of them.  I also checked all the Great Horned Owl and Northern Saw-whet Owl vocalizations in the Cornell Master Set and found nothing that matched.

It's possible that this is not a bird and perhaps a mammal.

Recorded in a wet forest adjacent to agricultural fields.  Sounds of traffic from nearby  interstate 95 are also audible.

Equipment: Sony PCM-M10 recorder and a Sennheiser ME67 microphone.
Modifications to the file: amplified by 10 dB.
author: Lance A. M. Benner

title: XC387173 Barred Owl (Strix varia)
location: Shenandoah National Park, Rockingham County, Virginia
description: My wife and I stopped off the main road at a dead end. I vocally imitated some Barred Owl calls. About 12 minutes later, a Barred Owl responded, flew within about 25 m of us, and landed on a branch. The owl then flew to a branch about 80 m away, called again (recorded here), then left. The owl returned about 3 minutes later, landed on another branch about 80 m away, called twice (recorded here), and then left the area. Recording was noise-reduced and normalized to -3 dB.

title: XC386358 Hammond's Flycatcher (Empidonax hammondii)
description: Empidonax. Small, active empid in alder next to open clearing in mixed woodland. Frequently flicked wings and tail up together. White eye ring prominent behind eye. Lower mandible orange with dark tip. Pale grey throat. Breast drab, belly yellow - markedly so when seen in shade, but barely visible when in sun. Thick whitish wingbars. Slight contrast between grey-toned head and olive-toned mantle. Repeated little "whit" or "tyip" calls. Initially suspected to be a Dusky, based in part on habitat, but Doug Robinson put me right.
author: Ben Phalan

description: This is two separate recordings paired back-to-back. Each recording has had the interval between vocalizations shortened significantly, as the recordings were made on the edge of a housing subdivision with interfering noises periodically in the background (as much of this as possible was spliced out). The bird itself was perched on a series of dead snags at a minimum distance of 50 m away (it moved around some during observation). The area is moderately wet, bog-like forest edge. The adjacent forest is a mixed-forest type with little to moderate interior disturbance, but surrounded by urban sprawl (sub-urban housing).

title: XC469745 Black-capped Chickadee (Poecile atricapillus)
secondary_labels: ['Certhia americana_Brown Creeper', "Calypte anna_Anna's Hummingbird", 'Spinus pinus_Pine Siskin', 'Empidonax difficilis_Pacific-slope Flycatcher', 'Pipilo maculatus_Spotted Towhee', 'Turdus migratorius_American Robin']
description: Normalized to -3dB. 68°F, 5% cloud cover, light intermittent breeze from west. Residential setting on the edge of a greenbelt with Douglas fir and Bigleaf Maple dominant. From 0:00 to 0:42 a single bird perched 10' high in a small birch tree giving tseet calls while preening (feather ruffling audible). From the same location it then gave a series of chick-a-dee type calls beginning around 0:34.5. At 1:11 a second bird flew in and both quickly moved to a medium sized bush 25' away, at which point vocalizations changed to gargle call types (could not tell which bird), then a mix of both chick-a-dee and gargles. Two more birds landed 50' to the north and gave chick-a-dee calls. There were 4 birds total, however neither group of 2 came within 50' of each other.
background: Brown Creeper (Certhia americana); Anna's Hummingbird (Calypte anna); Pine Siskin (Spinus pinus); Pacific-slope Flycatcher (Empidonax difficilis); Spotted Towhee (Pipilo maculatus); American Robin (Turdus migratorius)

title: XC150001 Yellow-bellied Flycatcher (Empidonax flaviventris)
location: Wekiwa Springs State Park, Apopka, Orange, Florida
description: This bird was recorded from a boat along the Wekiva River on March 1, 2013. The habitat is extensive hardwood floodplain swamp. It called repeatedly for quite some time but never showed itself. The call notes sound like a reasonably good fit to the "turee" type call of YBFL to me. However, this species is quite rare in Florida, especially in winter/spring. I'd appreciate thoughts on this one. I recorded this with my iphone 4s and amplified it slightly using Audacity. It is otherwise unedited. You have to forgive the background noise. Someone was digging through a pelican case on the aluminum boat hull and created a lot of noise. I isolated one call note and cleaned it up a bit. I'll upload that recording momentarily.
author: Graham Williams
